<em>This post was written by </em><a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/author/bob-ciura/articles#regular_articles\"><em>Bob Ciura</em></a><em> on December 21, 2016, for Sure Dividend</em></p> <p>There are two companies that dominate the U.S. toy industry: Mattel (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/MAT\" title=\"Mattel, Inc.\">MAT</a>) and Hasbro (<span class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\">NASDAQ:<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/HAS\" title=\"Hasbro, Inc.\">HAS</a></span>). Both companies pay dividends to shareholders. Mattel has a 5% dividend yield. Mattel may appeal more to investors looking for high yields. But, its higher yield <a href=\"https://www.suredividend.com/mattel-high-yield/?utm_source=bc&amp;utm_medium=sd&amp;utm_campaign=122116sd2\" rel=\"nofollow\">comes with significant risks</a>.</p> <p>On the other hand, Hasbro has a smaller dividend yield of 2.5%. This isn't too exciting of a dividend yield; the S&amp;P 500 Index on average yields about 2%. But the advantage for Hasbro is that it is a high dividend growth stock.</p> <p>Hasbro is a Dividend Achiever. To be a Dividend Achiever, a stock must increase its dividend for 10+ consecutive years. This is no small feat. You can see the entire <a href=\"https://www.suredividend.com/dividend-achievers-list/?utm_source=bc&amp;utm_medium=sd&amp;utm_campaign=122116sd2\" rel=\"nofollow\">list of all 273 Dividend Achievers here</a>.</p> <p>This article will discuss why Hasbro might be a good stock to put on your holiday shopping list.</p> <p><em></em><span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2016/12/23/saupload_Hasbro-e1482349059468.png\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"710\" data-height=\"355\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"true\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkdin=\"true\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2016/12/23/saupload_Hasbro-e1482349059468_thumb1.png\" data-width=\"640\" data-height=\"320\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"true\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkdin=\"true\" fetchpriority=\"high\"></a></span></p> <p><strong>Business Overview</strong></p> <p>Hasbro has a long and rich <a href=\"https://corporate.hasbro.com/images/Hasbro_Timeline.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">history</a>. Interestingly, its origins had little to do with toys.</p> <p>The company was founded in 1923 and was known as Hassenfeld Brothers. The company was named after its founders Henry, Hillel and Herman Hassenfeld. At first, the company sold textile remnants and soon expanded into pencil boxes and school supplies. It wouldn't make its first toy until the 1940s. The first toys it manufactured were doctor and nurse kits. In 1952, the company unveiled Mr. Potato Head, which is still popular today.</p> <p>Today, Hasbro generates more than $4 billion in annual revenue. The company is organized into three main operating segments:</p> <ul> <li>U.S. and Canada (56% of sales)</li> <li>International (41% of sales)</li> <li>Entertainment and Licensing (3% of sales)</li> </ul> <p>Hasbro's strategy is to maximize the potential of its brands across several key categories.</p> <p><em></em><span><a href=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2016/12/23/saupload_HAS-Brands.jpg\" rel=\"lightbox\" data-width=\"710\" data-height=\"529\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"true\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkdin=\"true\"><img src=\"https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2016/12/23/saupload_HAS-Brands_thumb1.jpg\" data-width=\"640\" data-height=\"477\" data-og-image-twitter_small_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_large_card=\"true\" data-og-image-twitter_image_post=\"true\" data-og-image-msn=\"true\" data-og-image-facebook=\"true\" data-og-image-google_news=\"true\" data-og-image-google_plus=\"true\" data-og-image-linkdin=\"true\" loading=\"lazy\"></a></span></p> <p><em>Source: </em><a href=\"https://files.shareholder.com/downloads/HAS/3478117474x0x911924/95E4CBCE-5024-4819-88CA-CE474565E780/Hasbro_Q3_2016_Earnings_Presentation_FINAL.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\"><em>Q3 Earnings</em></a></p>", "twitContent": "$HAS - Hasbro's Average Yield Is Hiding Its Dividend Growth Potential. https://seekingalpha.com/article/4032338-hasbros-average-yield-is-hiding-dividend-growth-potential?source=tweet ", "innerMarketing": null, "marketingBullet": "", "isMpwLocked": true, "isReit": false, "videoData": null, "marketingBulletVariant": null, "marketingBio": null, "audioDuration": null}, "relationships": {"author": {"data": {"id": "63883", "type": "author"}}, "sentiments": {"data": []}, "primaryTickers": {"data": [{"id": "4040", "type": "tag"}]}, "secondaryTickers": {"data": [{"id": "1748", "type": "tag"}]}, "otherTags": {"data": [{"id": "148873", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "156", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "17829", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "16549", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "326", "type": "tag"}, {"id": "17860", "type": "tag"}]}, "coAuthors": {"data": []}, "presentations": {"data": []}, "updates": {"data": []}, "corrections": {"data": []}}, "links": {"self": "/article/4032338-hasbros-average-yield-is-hiding-dividend-growth-potential", "canonical": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4032338-hasbros-average-yield-is-hiding-dividend-growth-potential", "uriImage": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2016/12/23/saupload_Hasbro-e1482349059468.png", "schemaImage": {"@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://static.seekingalpha.com/uploads/2016/12/23/saupload_Hasbro-e1482349059468.pn